Hypothesis Testing

Understanding Uncertainty

Introduction

  • Our goal today, is to read regression tables
  • These tools are very useful for thinking about first-order (predictive) uncertainty and second-order (model reliability) uncertainty
  • And, if you go around saying "I'm a data scientist", people will assume you know this material

The Sampling Distribution

  • We want to return to the concept of a sampling distribution
  • If you repeat an experiment over and over, then plot the KDE or ECDF, you are estimating something ($\mathbb{E}[ \hat{F}_n(x) ] = F(x)$)
  • What are you estimating?
  • It is essentially an estimate of the reliability of your statistical procedure: Given your measurement and analytics techniques, do you get a stable, coherent answer?
  • This is the sampling distribution, and becomes the foundation of all statistical procedures

Roadmap

  1. Bootstrap Inference
  2. Standard Errors
  3. Classical Hypothesis Testing

1. Bootstrap Inference

Bootstrapping

  • We have bootstrapped throughout class, but recall: To bootstrap the sampling distribution of a statistic $\hat{\theta}$, we

    1. Pick a large number, $B$, like 2500 or 5000 or 10000
    2. Resample the data, with replacement, $B$ times
    3. For each resample of the data, compute your statistic, $\hat{\theta}_b$
    4. The ECDF is an estimate of the sampling distribution of $\hat{\theta}$

  • Notice, this ECDF is not an estimate of the distribution of $\theta$, because $\theta$ is a number and not a random variable. This distribution is an estimate of statistical reliability, not $pr[\Theta \le \theta | \text{ data }]$

  • We are asking, "If you did this analysis on similar data many times, how much variation would there be in your estimates?"

  • We think this provides a useful way of capturing second-order uncertainty

Random Sampling and Representativeness

  • We should pause and point out: We're assuming that your sample is representative of the original population
  • If your sample has sampling bias and over-samples some subset of the population or the instruments you use for measurements have measurement bias and collect incorrect data, then your sample will differ systematically from the properties of the original population
  • Arguably, if your sample is too small for your modes of analysis, then you have sampling bias as well
  • Bootstrapping can't really fix this: Garbage in, garbage out

Case Study: Hedonic Pricing, Again

  • We'll look at the prices of housing in Ames, IA
  • The goal is to do a non-trivial example of extracting the sampling distribution of a statistic
  • We'll get the sampling distributions of the regression coefficients

y = data['price']
X = data.drop('price',axis=1)
vars = X.columns
print(vars)

# OLS function
def OLS(X, y):
    try:
        # Try exact OLS
        beta = np.linalg.solve(X.T @ X, X.T @ y)
    except np.linalg.LinAlgError:
        # If singular, regularize
        print('Whoops! Singular. L2/Ridge stabilizing...')
        lam = 10e-6
        beta = np.linalg.solve(X.T @ X + lam * np.eye(X.shape[1]), X.T @ y)
    error = y - X @ beta
    sigma = np.sqrt( np.sum( error ** 2 )/ len(y) )
    return beta, sigma

beta_hat, sigma_hat = OLS(X,y)

# Bootstrap the sampling distribution of coefficients
def boot(data):
    data_s = data.sample(frac=1,replace=True)
    y_s = data_s['price']
    X_s = data_s.drop('price',axis=1)
    beta_hat_s = OLS(X_s,y_s)
    return beta_hat_s

n_boot = 5_000
replications = [ boot(data) for s in range(n_boot) ]

# Extract coefficients for each bootstrap replication and plot:
def inference_plots(i, replications):
    these_coefs = [ row[0][i] for row in replications]
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(14,5))
    sns.kdeplot(these_coefs,ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title(f'Density: {vars[i]}')
    sns.ecdfplot(these_coefs,ax=axes[1])
    axes[1].set_title(f'Distribution: {vars[i]}')
    return vars[i]

# Plot sampling distributions for all the coefficients
[ inference_plots(i, replications) for i in range(len(vars)) ]

Communicating Results

  • How do we communicate our results? These plots can be difficult to interpret and understand.
  • A 90/95/99% (percentile bootstrap) confidence interval reports the (.05, .95)/(.025, .975)/(.005, .995) quantiles of the bootstrapped sampling distribution.
  • This bounds some proportion of bootstrap results in an interval, giving a more concrete answer to what values the coefficient is likely to take.
  • These CIs put half the "weight" in each tail, so the 90% confidence interval corresponds to the .05 and .95 quantiles, not the .1 and .9 quantiles (which would be an 80% CI)
In[5]:
# Extract coefficients for each bootstrap replication and plot:
def inference(i, replications, alpha = None, plot = True):
    these_coefs = [ row[0][i] for row in replications]
    if alpha is not None:
        L = np.quantile(these_coefs, alpha/2 ) # Two-tailed interval
        H = np.quantile(these_coefs, (1- alpha/2) ) # Two-tailed interval
        ci_text = f'Confidence interval for {vars[i]}: ({round(L,4)}, {round(H,4)})'

    if plot:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(14,5))
        sns.kdeplot(these_coefs,ax=axes[0])
        axes[0].set_title(f'Density: {vars[i]}')
        sns.ecdfplot(these_coefs,ax=axes[1])
        axes[1].set_title(f'Distribution: {vars[i]}')

        if alpha is not None:
            axes[0].axvline(L, color='darkorange', linestyle='--')
            axes[0].axvline(H, color='darkorange', linestyle='--')
            axes[1].axvline(L, color='darkorange', linestyle='--')
            axes[1].axvline(H, color='darkorange', linestyle='--')
    return ci_text

Hypothesis Testing

  • In science, you cannot prove hypotheses, only refute them (e.g. Karl Popper, "A hypothesis can't be right unless it can be proven wrong"; even one counterexample can disprove a hypothesis)
  • So we set up scenarios in which we want to reject the "null" hypothesis, and then consult the evidence
  • The most common null hypothesis is that the true $\mu_0 = 0$, and the confidence interval contains zero
  • For your particular application, it might be something else (e.g. $\mu_0=1$ might have special significance, or $\mu_0\gtrless 0$)
  • To run a hypothesis test, we ask, "Are the data consistent with the null? If not, we reject it in favor of the alternative hypothesis."
  • So the null $\mu_0$ is something we pick before we even get started on our test (e.g. pre-registering a randomized controlled trial), assume it is true, and then attempt to show it is inconsistent with the data
  • This is a data-drive reductio ad absurdum: If the data are inconsistent with the null, we'll reject it as implausible

From CI to Hypothesis

  • The confidence interval is the $(\alpha/2,1-\alpha/2)$-quantile interval of bootstrap replications ($\alpha = .1/.05/.01$)
  • We call $\alpha$ the level of the test and it corresponds to a $100 \times (1-\alpha)$% confidence interval (90%, 95%, 99%)
  • These are typically two-tailed tests, so that $\alpha/2$ probability is included in each of the tails of the density of the sampling distribution

Here we fail to reject:

In[7]:
inference(1, replications, alpha=.1) # Rejecting the null

Hypothesis Testing with Packages

  • Let's take Age of the dwelling.
  • We would say, "I am testing whether the Age coefficient is statistically significantly different from 0 at the 0.1 level (=90% confidence)." We consult our 90%-CI for Age above: (-1007.186, -916.865). This does not contain zero. "We reject the null hypothesis that the Age coefficient is zero at the 0.1 level."
  • Alternatively, take 2Story. We would say, "I am testing whether the 2Story coefficient is statistically significantly different from 0 at the 0.1 level (=90% confidence)." We consult our 90%-CI for 2Story above: (-3577.244, 26156.690). This does contain zero. "We fail to reject the null hypothesis that the 2Story coefficient is zero at the 0.1 level."

  • Percentile Bootstrapped CIs tend to be wider than the ones reported from statistical packages, which use asymptotic formulas rather than data-driven methods.
  • My opinion is that the difference tells you how big the approximation is: If the asymptotic and bootstrap CIs are close, then the approximation isn't large. If they're very different, then you're assuming you have more precision than you probably really do.
  • There are many versions of Bootstrapped CIs, which tend to be smaller and closer to the asymptotic forumulas: If your bootstrapped sampling distribution looks skewed, it can impact performance, and a more complex version of the bootstrap CI might work better

$p$-Values

  • The $p$-value is an attempt to avoid picking the level $\alpha$ of the test; think of it like an "adaptive CI" that adjusts the level until we just barely reject the null
  • So the confidence interval is the $(\alpha,1-\alpha)$ interval of bootstrap replications, and we call $\alpha$ the level of the test
  • Instead, if we adjusted $\alpha$ to be as small as possible without including 0, how small could we make it?
  • This quantity is called a $p$-value: "What is the minimum level I can get away with and still reject the null?"

2. Standard Errors

What is StatsModels doing?

  • To fill in that blank, we need to introduce some classical statistical concepts
  • Like many of the topics we cover, it's hard to understand the big picture from the individual pieces, so you have to pay attention to the pieces to get the payoff
  • We'll take a step back to look at estimation of the mean, to motivate the big idea: Standard Errors (of an estimate)

Independent and Identically Distributed Sequences (iid)

  • A fundamental concept in probability and statistics is the abstract idea of running an "experiment" over and over, and computing statistics for the results
  • Let $x_1$ be the result of the first experiment, $x_2$ the result of the second, and so on
  • Assume that the draws $x_1, x_2, ...$
    • are identically distributed: They are all drawn from the same distribution function and all have the same mean $\mu$ and variance $\sigma^2$
    • are independent: The outcome of draw $x_n$ doesn't affect the outcome of any draw $x_m$, $m \neq n$
  • The sample average of our experimental sequence is $$ \bar{X}_n = \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i $$ and the sample variance of our experimental sequence is $$ \bar{s}_n^2 = \dfrac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (x_i - \bar{X}_n)^2 $$

Independent and Identically Distributed Sequences (iid)

  • The sample average and sample variance are now, themselves, random variables, with their own outcomes, events, probabilities, and so on
  • What is the expected value of $\bar{X}_n$? $$ \mathbb{E}[\bar{X}_n] = \mathbb{E}\left[ \dfrac{1}{n} \left( X_1 + X_2 + ... + X_n \right) \right] = \dfrac{\mathbb{E}[X_1] + ... + \mathbb{E}[X_n]}{n} = \dfrac{\mu + ... + \mu}{n} = \dfrac{n\mu}{n} = \mu $$

Standard Error of the Mean

  • Likewise, but with slightly different steps: \begin{alignat*}{2} \mathbb{V}[\bar{X}_n] &=& \mathbb{V}\left[\frac{1}{n}(X_1 + X_2 + ... + X_n)\right] \\ &=& \frac{1}{n^2} \mathbb{V}[X_1 + X_2 + ... + X_n] \quad \text{(HW 6)}\\ &=& \frac{1}{n^2} \left( \mathbb{V}[X_1] + \mathbb{V}[X_2] + ... + \mathbb{V}[X_n] \right) \quad \text{(Independence)}\\ &=& \frac{n}{n^2} \sigma^2 \\ &=& \frac{\sigma^2}{n} \end{alignat*}
  • The standard deviation of the sample mean is written as $$ SE[\bar{X}_n] = \dfrac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} $$ In hypothesis testing, you will see this $1/\sqrt{n}$ term appear everywhere: It is what drives the variance of our estimates to zero as our sample size gets large; this is part of why we want "big data"
  • This kind of quantity, $\sigma/\sqrt{n}$, is so ubiquitous it gets a name: STANDARD ERROR

Standard Errors

Please record this in your forever memory:

THE STANDARD ERROR OF AN ESTIMATE

IS THE STANDARD DEVIATION

OF ITS SAMPLING DISTRIBUTION

Standard Errors

  • For the mean, the SE was just the sample standard deviation divided by $\sqrt{n}$
  • One of the main jobs of statisticians is to derive standard errors for their models
  • For more complex statistical models like regressions, the standard errors are more complex
    • For linear regression, the standard errors are the square roots of the diagonal elements of $\hat{\sigma}^2 (X^{\top}X)^{-1}$
    • For general maximum likelihood estimation, we can compute standard errors from the shape of the log-likelihood function (diagonal elements of the inverse of the information matrix)

Bootstrapping SE's

  • We can compute a standard error for any quantity using bootstrapping. We compute the sample standard deviation of our bootstrap replication values: $$ SE[\hat{\theta}] = \sqrt{\frac{1}{B-1} \sum_{b=1}^B (\hat{\theta}_b - \bar{\hat{\theta}})^2} $$ where $\bar{\hat{\theta}} = \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^B \hat{\theta}_{b}$

## Bootstrapped Standard Errors:

def boot_se(vars, replications):
    se = []
    for i in range(len(vars)):
        these_coefs = [ row[0][i] for row in replications]
        theta_hat_bar = np.mean(these_coefs)
        err = these_coefs - theta_hat_bar
        se_theta = np.sqrt(np.sum(err ** 2)/(len(these_coefs)-1))
        se.append(se_theta)
    result = pd.DataFrame({'variable':vars,'standard_error':se})
    return result

se_boot = boot_se(vars, replications)

Classical Hypothesis Testing

Making Sense of Tests

  • We have now covered most of the StatsModels output table
  • Remember, we can rewrite any estimator (since it is a random variable) $\hat{X}_n$ with a mean $\mu$ and a standard deviation $SE[\hat{X}_n]$ as $$ \hat{X}_n = \mu + SE[\hat{X}_n] t $$ where $n$ is sample size and $t$ is some random variable with a mean of 0 and a variance of 1.
  • If we rearrange this, we get $$ t = \dfrac{ \hat{X}_n - \mu}{SE[\hat{X}_n]} $$
  • We are thinking as follows: We have an estimate $\hat{X}$ of some value $\mu$, and the standard error of $\hat{X}$ is $SE[\hat{X}]$. Then the realized error term would be $t$
  • We call $t$ the test statistic

Central Limit Theorem

  • Suppose $X_1, X_2, ... $ is a sequence of iid random variables with $\mathbb{E}[X_i]=\mu$ and $\mathbb{V}[X_i] = \sigma^2 < \infty$. Then the random variable $$ t_n = \dfrac{\hat{X}_n - \mu}{SE[\hat{X}_n]}$$ converges in distribution to a standard normal distribution.

  • In symbols, what this means is $$ \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left[ \frac{\hat{X}_n-\mu}{SE[\hat{X}_n]} \le z\right] = \Phi \left(z \right) $$ where $\Phi()$ is the standard normal cdf.

  • This allows us to approximate the sampling distribution with a standard normal, as long as we rescale our values as $(\hat{X}_n-\mu)/SE[\hat{X}_n]$

  • It is not "hard" to prove the CLT, but it requires a bunch of detours into concepts from statistics that don't have an obvious payoff for us (e.g. moment generating functions), so we'll skip it.

  • Any ideas that flow from this kind of result are called asymptotic statistics, since they replace the finite sample reality with the infinite sample limiting approximation; they are asymptotic approximations

Using the CLT

  • Let's see how this works in a plot
  • The dashed line is bootstrapping, the solid line is the CLT
  • We are approximating the sampling distribution of the test statistic by a standard normal
In[16]:
from scipy.stats import norm

i = 1
print(vars[i])
these_coefs = [ row[0][i] for row in replications]
n = len(these_coefs)
x_bar = np.mean(these_coefs)
x = these_coefs-x_bar # Recenter the values

std_err = np.mean( (x) **2 )/np.sqrt( n )

grid = np.linspace(-100,100,500)

pdf = norm.pdf(grid, loc=0, scale=std_err)
cdf = norm.cdf(grid, loc=0, scale=std_err)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(14,5))
sns.lineplot(x=grid,y=pdf,ax=axes[0])
sns.kdeplot(x,ax=axes[0],linestyle='dashed')
axes[0].set_title(f'Density: {vars[i]}')
sns.lineplot(x=grid,y=cdf,ax=axes[1])
sns.ecdfplot(x,ax=axes[1],linestyle='dashed')
axes[1].set_title(f'Distribution: {vars[i]}')

Constructing Asymptotic CIs

  • This is great: Where do CIs come from?
  • If $t_n$ has the standard normal distribution, we can ask, "What is the probability that $t_n$ is at least $c$-far away from 0?" or $$ \mathbb{P}\left[ |t_n | \ge c \right]? $$
  • Well, let's play with that: \begin{alignat*}{2} \mathbb{P}\left[ |t_n | \ge c \right] &=& \mathbb{P}\left[ \left| \frac{\hat{\theta}-\mu}{SE[\hat{\theta}]} \right| \ge c \right] \\ &=& \mathbb{P}\left[ c \ge \frac{\mu - \hat{\theta}}{SE[\hat{\theta}]} \ge -c \right] \\ &=& \mathbb{P}\left[ c \times SE[\hat{\theta}] \ge \mu - \hat{\theta} \ge -c \times SE[\hat{\theta}] \right] \\ &=& \mathbb{P}\left[ \hat{\theta}+ c \times SE[\hat{\theta}] \ge \mu \ge \hat{\theta} -c \times SE[\hat{\theta}] \right] \end{alignat*}
  • This thing: $$ (\hat{\theta} -c \times SE[\hat{\theta}], \hat{\theta}+ c \times SE[\hat{\theta}]) $$ is the confidence interval, derived from a probability statement about whether the probability that the test statistic is large

The Hypothesis

  • We don't know what $\mu$ is, or else we wouldn't be here
  • But for a variety of values (e.g. 0, 1, -9.81 $m/s^2$), we can associate $\mu$ with that value, and call it the Null Hypothesis (as earlier)
  • The most common null, by far, is that $\mu = 0$
  • We are then saying, "Given the data, how probable is it that $\mu=0$ is covered by this confidence interval?"
  • But the uncertainty is about our measurements and statistical methodology, not the true $\mu$, which is a constant

Fixing the Level $\alpha$

  • If we were to fix, say, $$ \mathbb{P}\left[ |t_n | \ge c \right] = .9 $$ and solve for $c$, we'd get a 90% CI.

  • Because these values come from the standard normal and the confidence levels are standard, we get this table:

Confidence Level Quantile Used Critical Value
90% $.90 = \int_{-c}^{c} \phi(z)dz$ $c = 1.645$
95% $.95 = \int_{-c}^{c} \phi(z)dz$ $c = 1.96$
99% $.99 = \int_{-c}^{c} \phi(z)dz$ $c = 2.576$

The Standard Confidence Intervals

  • So the standard confidence intervals are $$ \text{CI}_{90} = (\hat{\theta} -1.645 \times SE[\hat{\theta}], \hat{\theta}+ 1.645 \times SE[\hat{\theta}]) $$ $$ \text{CI}_{95} = (\hat{\theta} -1.96 \times SE[\hat{\theta}], \hat{\theta}+ 1.96 \times SE[\hat{\theta}]) $$ $$ \text{CI}_{99} = (\hat{\theta} -2.576 \times SE[\hat{\theta}], \hat{\theta}+ 2.576 \times SE[\hat{\theta}]) $$
  • Notice how we've subsumed the standard normal into the 1.645/1.96/2.576 numbers: We don't want to worry about using $\Phi()$ because we've already "looked up" the relevant values for 0.90/0.95/0.99
In[17]:

$p$-Values

  • The $p$-value is the smallest level $\alpha$ (confidence $= 1-\alpha$) of the test for which the null is rejected
  • The formal definition of a $p$-value is $$ p = \mathbb{P}[ |z| \ge |t_n|] $$ or, "What is the probability that a draw from a normal distribution is at least as extreme as our observed value, assuming the null is true?"
  • In practice, what this means is, "What is the least level $\alpha$ at which I would reject the null?"
  • This is conceptually more difficult to understand, but avoids the 90/95/99% arbitrariness of hypothesis testing based on confidence intervals
  • Calculating it is deceptively easy: $$ p = \Phi( - |t_n|) + (1-\Phi(|t_n|)) = 2 \times \Phi( - |t_n|) $$ This is because we're computing the area in the tails that are at least $-|t_n|$ away from zero, and $\Phi(-|t_n|) = 1-\Phi(|t_n|)$.

Statistical Table

  • You can now make sense of any statistical table:
    • Coefficients: point estimates
    • Standard Error: standard deviation of the sampling distribution for the coefficients
    • $t$-stat: coefficient divided by standard error
    • $p$-value: the minimum significance level at which the null hypothesis could be rejected
    • Confidence intervals: coefficient $\pm$ 1.645/1.96/2.576 $\times$ the standard error
  • To show how this works, let's recreate the StatsModels output table using only their coefficient estimates and standard errors

ci_L = coef - 1.96 * std_err
ci_H = coef + 1.96 * std_err

                        'std_err':std_err,
                        't-stats':t_stats,
                        'p-value':p_value,

                        'CI, upper': ci_H}),3)

Miscellaneous

The $t$ distribution

  • In some situations, you don't have a lot of data, and those data are used when estimating the parameters of your model
  • The degrees of freedom is the sample size, minus the number of parameters (essentially, rows minus columns)
  • In such a situation, the asymptotic normal approximation is overly optimistic
  • In particular, the point estimation of $\hat{\beta}$ and $\hat{\sigma}$ both use data, reducing the "degrees of freedom" that are available to conduct the hypothesis test, relative to an alternative world in which you had an infinite amount of data
  • A statistician working at Guinness showed that if you replace the Normal distribution with the $t$-distribution, the results are more accurate when the sample size is small (or... just bootstrap)
In[21]:
## T versus Normal Plot

from scipy.stats import norm, t

# Domain for plotting
x = np.linspace(-4, 4, 400)

# t distributions with various dfs
dfs = [3, 5, 10, 30]
pdf_ts = {df: t.pdf(x, df=df) for df in dfs}

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))

# Plot normal
sns.lineplot(x=x, y=pdf_norm, label='Normal(0,1)', linewidth=2)

# Plot t-dfs
for df in dfs:
    sns.lineplot(x=x, y=pdf_ts[df], label=f't(df={df})', linestyle='--')

plt.title("Normal vs Student-t Densities")
plt.xlabel("x")
plt.ylabel("Density")
plt.legend(title="Distribution")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

  • So if your sample size less the number of parameters exceeds 30, $t$ is basically the standard normal
  • This is similar to how the bootstrap tends to put "more weight in the tails" compared to the standard normal
  • Perhaps that sounds like you'll always have enough degrees of freedom to use the standard normal, but

Conclusion

  • These are the basic tools of statistical inference: Sampling Distribution, Standard Error, Confidence Interval, Hypothesis Test
  • This methodology gets abused quite regularly, which is unfortunate
  • People will expect you to be able to make sense of regression results and correctly interpret these tables
  • A/B Testing is, again, just comparing two groups' outcomes by bootstrapping or regression; the test part is whether the average difference between groups is statistically significant
